<br>
At the beginning of the game, there maybe 64 players signed on to go exploring their character, the quests, and the encounters (most players like to try out the new games immediately when they can, which might lead to many people on right at the opening whether or not they plan on sticking around for the long run).  With no experience given to some roaming monsters, the slow spawn time of the dungeons, and possibly 60 people looking for something to do...<br>
<br>
Will Shroud have the amount of content to pacify and entertain 60 people at once in the beginning?  Although most playing on the server might know eachother and be friends with eachother, my bet is that (especially early on) people are going to be looking for the thrill of the gaming environment as much as the social aspect of the server.  How will you ensure that the people playing are not going to feel restricted in their options early on? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#97694F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub26.ezboard.com/usegalsoulsaver.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Segal SoulSaver</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://wwp.icq.com/scripts/online.dll?icq=112539253&img=5" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lead-GM</span><br>  Posts: 2584<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(1/21/02 2:14:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub26.ezboard.com/fapex71990frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=187.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The 'Vision' (tm)</span><hr size=1> I really dont expect 64 people on at once, even at the beginning, more like 40-45 maximum.   Most of these people are really only going to play during normal hours (i.e. 5-10 on weekdays, longer on weekends).   But since all the content is reuseable, there maybe some overcrowding initially but it will thin out.   Try going to an Everquest server on release day, 300 in Greater Faydark.  If Sony cant do it with multi-million dollar budgets, then I dont expect I can either.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, after the first couple of weeks, I dont think it will be that big of an issue.   Take the campaign module that comes with the game, it has 60 hours of gameplay included.   If you staggered 6 man groups through it in a persistent style world, you could conceivably host an unlimited number of people.   The bigger problem with content is maintaining content on the back end (i.e. making sure you have enough content continueing to enter the game to keep people occupied.)<br>
<br>
But as a more direct answer to your question, I plan on doing the following.<br>
<br>
1) Area Creation - Creating areas is fast and easy (the devil is in the details as they say).  So creating a number of areas with appropriately leveled mobs is pretty easy.  Then, as time allows, come back in and revamp them to be more intricate and challenging.<br>
<br>
2) Quests - Completing quests will be difficult and time consuming.   Players will have to band together to share knowledge to try and solve them.  This will be a major enterprise initially as players explore the areas and find the quests.<br>
<br>
3) Player-created areas - I expect players to add new content, many of our members are very creative and have already expressed interest in trying to develop content.  Further, people cant complain about a particular type of content missing from the game, my answer will be &quot;No Thieves guild in yet, why dont you create one.&quot;<br>
<br>
4) Community Aspects - NWN is designed in a modular style, scripts and such can easily be ported from one module to another.  I expect to borrow quite a few scripts right out of the official module, change a few words and you would never recognize them.  This will be a huge timesaver, once you invent the wheel, no one else has too.<br>
<br>
5) Dedication - It really all comes down to dedication.  Am I willing to work 40-50 hours per week for the first month to make sure that people have a world they can adventure in?  Sure, I have been waiting for this opportunity for nearly 3 years and cant wait to get started.<br>
<br>
